**Two Principles That Prevent the Majority of A02 Failures**

+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| **Principle 1 --- Never implement | **Principle 2 --- Never make your |
| your own cryptography**           | own cryptographic decisions**     |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| Every serious cryptographic break | ECB mode is available in every    |
| in real-world software in the     | cryptographic library because     |
| last decade came from one of two  | there are legitimate use cases    |
| sources: a developer who thought  | (single-block encryption of       |
| a simple XOR or Caesar-cipher     | random data). The library cannot  |
| variant was \"good enough,\" or a | know that you\'re using it for    |
| developer who combined standard   | structured multi-block data where |
| primitives incorrectly.           | ECB is dangerous.                 |
|                                   |                                   |
| **The correct response to any     | **The correct response to any     |
| cryptographic requirement is to   | cryptographic choice is: use the  |
| find a well-reviewed, maintained  | library\'s recommended default,   |
| library that handles the use case | not the most convenient option.** |
| --- and use its defaults.**       |                                   |
|                                   | Fernet uses AES-128-CBC by        |
| For Python: cryptography.fernet   | default. **You do not need to     |
| for symmetric, bcrypt for         | choose a cipher mode.** That is   |
| passwords, PyJWT for tokens.      | the point. When a library makes   |
| These are correct by default. Use | the cryptographic decision for    |
| them.                             | you --- use that library.         |
+-----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Practical connection:** The TLS demo in this module demonstrates
  Column 1 (Transport) --- ZAP\'s MITM shows the consequence of a browser
  trusting an additional root CA. The Juice Shop coupon and score
  challenges demonstrate Column 3 (Application data) --- the coupon
  signing algorithm is predictable because the key is not
  cryptographically random. ShopCo Flaw 3 (MD5 passwords cracked in the
  Module 4 HashCat exercise) is Column 2 (Password Storage). Columns 1--4
  together cover every A02 failure class you have encountered across this
  course.

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
